issue.title: [BUG]: Hanging on Compiling Julia backend
issue.body:
### What happened?

On a clean install of pysr in a virtual environment (arch: Apple Silicon M3Max MBP, os: macOS Sequoia 15.1.1 ), running the example code in the quickstart section in terminal, I've run into an issue where calling calling model.fit() hangs at the point where the Julia backend is being compiled.  The install proceeded without issue, and no errors are thrown prior to calling fit.  The terminal process had to be terminated after an hour with no output after 'Compiling Julia backend...'.

I've replicated the issue on clean installs.  Though, strangely, on a 2017 iMac with an Intel chipset, the quickstart code ran smoothly without hanging and gave the expected output.



### Version

1.5.2

### Operating System

macOS

### Package Manager

pip

### Interface

IPython Terminal

### Relevant log output

```shell

```

### Extra Info

_No response_

nodes.body:
Weird. What does activity monitor say, is it actually running something, or is it crashed?

Are you feeding stderr into any log files by any chance?

Finally, what happens if you run it as a script, like `python example.py`

Activity monitor showed CPU activity associated to task drop to 0.0% after 'Compiling Julia backend...' output.  

No crashes reported in console. Nothing written to file from stderr.

Running the quickstart code script gave same result as running directly in terminal.
So juliacall should have automatically installed julia. Are you able to run basic commands within Julia itself (using that same binary)? Like just `julia -e 'println("hello")'`.
No, trying to run julia commands results in 'julia: command not found'.
Where did it install Julia? It's probably in `~/.julia/bin/julia`. Run that
Hmm, ~/.julia exists but it isn't clear if/where it was installed; no ./bin appears in ~/.julia, and 'which julia' returns nothing.
Can you use juliacall? https://juliapy.github.io/PythonCall.jl/stable/juliacall/ Just to see if anything obvious is broken
juliacall appears to be working fine.
What part of the code does it exit if you do `ctrl-c`?
ctrl-c did not immediately kill the process and has not (5 min and counting) yet given any report of where in the code it was killed.

ctrl-\ maybe?

Can you try with a fresh Python/Julia installation on your machine? Since it works on other macs (I do my work on an M1 MacBook), and you could run it fine on a different computer, I really can’t think of what else it could be. Especially without other logs, it’s a bit of a mystery. Any other info you can gather would be helpful
Also try different version of Python if possible, and say which ones were tried

Will test with another fresh Python/Julia.  Currently the tests have been with python 3.11.8.

> `ctrl-\` maybe?

Looking at Activity Monitor for the python3.11 process testing before and after % cpu drops to 0.0:

I wonder if it has to do with your Python appearing to be installed by anaconda. Do you think there is any possibility it installed the x86 version of Python, and thus, Rosetta had to translate all the calls into ARM instructions? The error stacktrace seems like it's actually running, but just super slow so I feel like an explanation is just that you were running a Rosetta-translated x86 version of Python/Julia and therefore were incredibly slow due to all the x86->ARM instruction translation.


And I guess your fresh install of Python correctly installed the ARM version of Python/Julia, and fixed these issues?

That is exactly what happened!  The python build that anaconda installed in the venv where I was doing the testing was h9f0c242_0_cpython, which is x86, and so the Rosetta translation was the culprit causing the slow down.
